.<img width="1200" height="702" class="wp-image-1340516" style="width: 800px;" src="https://cdn.vanguardngr.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/DMO.png" alt="DMO, World Bank push states’ debt management laws" srcset="https://cdn.vanguardngr.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/DMO.png?width=1200&amp;auto_optimize=medium 1200w, https://cdn.vanguardngr.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/DMO-300x176.png?width=300&amp;auto_optimize=medium 300w, https://cdn.vanguardngr.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/DMO-1024x599.png?width=1024&amp;auto_optimize=medium 1024w, https://cdn.vanguardngr.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/DMO-768x449.png?width=768&amp;auto_optimize=medium 768w, https://cdn.vanguardngr.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/DMO-58x34.png?width=58&amp;auto_optimize=medium 58w, https://cdn.vanguardngr.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/DMO-260x152.png?width=260&amp;auto_optimize=medium 260w, https://cdn.vanguardngr.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/DMO-200x117.png?width=200&amp;auto_optimize=medium 200w, https://cdn.vanguardngr.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/DMO-560x328.png?width=560&amp;auto_optimize=medium 560w" sizes="(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px" />  As a sign of commitment to promptly honour its debts obligations always, Nigeria has redeemed its 300 million dollars diaspora bond which matured on June 27. This is according to a statement by the Debt Management Office (DMO) on its website on Tuesday. The DMO said that the diaspora bond was issued on June 27, 2017 for a tenor of five years in the International Capital Market. It added that the country had earlier redeemed 500 million dollars Eurobond bond in 2021. It said that proceeds of the diaspora bond were used, partly, to finance the deficit in the 2017 budget. The DMO said that the diaspora bond also created an opportunity for Nigerians in the diaspora to invest in their home country. “With the redemption of 500 million dollars Eurobond in January 2021, and recently the 300 million dollars diaspora bond , the government has increased investors’ confidence. “It shows the country’s commitment and ability to fulfil its debt obligations at maturity, thereby reinforcing its presence in the International Capital Market, ” it said.    The Federal Republic of Nigeria through the Debt Management Office (DMO) has pioneered the inaugural listing of Diaspora Bond on the FMDQ OTC Securities Exchange platform. In "News" By Peter Egwuatu The United Bank for Africa (UBA) on Wednesday, redeemed its debut $500 million 5-year Eurobond notes with the maturity date of June 8, 2022. The bank in a statement stated: “ Issued in 2017, the five-year bond was offered at a coupon rate of 7.75%, and raised… In "Business" Nigeria tops the top ten remittance recipients in Africa with $20.77bn In "Viewpoint"